00:05:50.490 --> 00:05:51.691
He looks at the poster.

00:05:52.260 --> 00:05:56.010
There isn't anybody that has
a disability like him.

00:05:56.611 --> 00:05:58.831
His spirit is down.
Obi feels sad.

00:05:59.221 --> 00:06:02.461
He feels like he's not included,
and he hurts.

00:06:03.120 --> 00:06:05.010
With these two illustrations in mind,

00:06:05.941 --> 00:06:08.436
I would love to introduce
my topic for today,

00:06:09.150 --> 00:06:11.341
Invisible Until It Hurts;

00:06:11.611 --> 00:06:15.235
Rethinking Brand Design
Through the Lens of Accessibility.

00:06:22.470 --> 00:06:29.041
Accessibility does not limit creativity,
unlike the popular thoughts of people.

00:06:29.550 --> 00:06:30.550
People think,

00:06:30.751 --> 00:06:34.620
"If my design is accessible,
I'll not be able to explore

00:06:35.040 --> 00:06:37.229
my creativity."
This is wrong.

00:06:38.461 --> 00:06:41.428
Accessibility does not limit creativity.

00:06:42.900 --> 00:06:47.550
Rather, accessibility in design
ensures that all people,

00:06:48.120 --> 00:06:52.021
especially those with disabilities,
can perceive,

00:06:52.230 --> 00:06:56.276
understand, and navigate,
even interact with design.

00:07:00.601 --> 00:07:04.090
These disabilities can present
themselves in different formats.

00:07:04.091 --> 00:07:07.530
It can be visual disabilities
like low vision

00:07:08.131 --> 00:07:09.527
or color blindness.

00:07:09.528 --> 00:07:12.469
It could be auditory disabilities
like hearing loss,

00:07:12.470 --> 00:07:14.371
and people who are deaf completely.

00:07:14.881 --> 00:07:19.211
It could be cognitive disabilities
like dyslexia, ADHD.

00:07:19.560 --> 00:07:24.721
It could be motor disabilities
where the user is a wheelchair user

00:07:24.930 --> 00:07:29.881
or an amputee, or someone
with Parkinson's disease

00:07:29.940 --> 00:07:32.472
or other motor disabilities.

00:07:34.470 --> 00:07:36.645
Now, that's our topic for today.

00:07:37.081 --> 00:07:38.311
Brand design is

00:07:39.001 --> 00:07:43.830
a visual and sensory system
that communicates who a brand is

00:07:43.950 --> 00:07:45.541
and what it represents.

00:07:46.440 --> 00:07:47.688
I'm sure you'll be surprised.

00:07:47.689 --> 00:07:50.340
Sensory system is not just visual.

00:07:51.780 --> 00:07:57.061
I hope I get to correct the notion today
that brand design is just visual.

00:07:57.511 --> 00:08:02.641
Because a brand should be able
to communicate what they stand for,

00:08:02.670 --> 00:08:04.007
not just visually.

00:08:04.008 --> 00:08:08.788
People should also be able to perceive
what a brand represents,

00:08:08.789 --> 00:08:14.443
either through hearing them
or feeling what they have to offer.

00:08:17.160 --> 00:08:21.282
Brand design gives a brand
its voice and its personality.

00:08:22.394 --> 00:08:26.251
Now, when accessibility comes in,
it ensures that that voice

00:08:26.310 --> 00:08:28.291
that is communicated is heard,

00:08:28.920 --> 00:08:32.131
understood, and be able to be used

00:08:32.821 --> 00:08:34.127
by everyone.

00:08:34.698 --> 00:08:38.216
When brand design
and accessibility come together,

00:08:38.217 --> 00:08:40.997
it forms an accessible brand design.

00:08:43.471 --> 00:08:48.049
A brand is experienced mainly visually
through colors,

00:08:48.480 --> 00:08:52.110
logo, fonts, imagery, and layout.

00:08:52.320 --> 00:08:56.431
It can also be experienced
through the brand's voice and tone.

00:08:58.050 --> 00:09:01.698
These are the building blocks
that make up a brand design.

00:09:02.580 --> 00:09:05.328
This means that for a brand
to be accessible,

00:09:05.881 --> 00:09:09.168
a brand needs to have
accessible brand assets.

00:09:10.831 --> 00:09:13.531
What are we going to learn
in today's discussion?

00:09:14.100 --> 00:09:17.191
In the course of this talk,
we'll be able to one,

00:09:17.430 --> 00:09:19.831
know how to spot accessibility issues.

00:09:20.220 --> 00:09:24.181
Two, know how to fix
this accessibility issue spotted.

00:09:24.601 --> 00:09:29.963
Three, learn the effects of these issues
on people with disabilities.

00:09:30.501 --> 00:09:34.410
Four, learn about the challenges
that brand designers encounter

00:09:34.440 --> 00:09:38.123
in brand design when trying
to implement accessibility.

00:09:38.492 --> 00:09:39.492
Finally,

00:09:39.930 --> 00:09:44.661
learn how brands and users
benefit from brand accessibility.

00:09:46.641 --> 00:09:49.680
Now, let us begin
with accessibility in typography.

00:09:50.370 --> 00:09:53.700
When accessibility
in typography is mentioned,

00:09:53.761 --> 00:09:59.003
we're talking about the creation of fonts
and also the usage of fonts.

00:10:00.384 --> 00:10:05.310
It can be used via its weight,
its style, or its size.

00:10:05.611 --> 00:10:08.004
That means it can be light or bold.

00:10:08.005 --> 00:10:11.850
It can be Serif, Sans Serif,
or decorative,

00:10:12.000 --> 00:10:13.801
or it can be large or small.

00:10:14.401 --> 00:10:18.781
The ability to implement
these features properly,

00:10:19.471 --> 00:10:24.080
including people with disability,
paves way for accessibility in typography.

00:10:25.020 --> 00:10:30.146
Now, let us learn about how to spot
some of the accessibility issues

00:10:30.147 --> 00:10:32.430
in typography and how to fix them.

00:10:33.720 --> 00:10:36.270
The first one is the text being too small.

00:10:36.780 --> 00:10:42.270
Sometimes, the text in a brand can be
less than 14 to 16 pixels for the body,

00:10:42.540 --> 00:10:43.801
and this is not accessible.

00:10:44.100 --> 00:10:48.091
This makes the bodies illegible
for people to read,

00:10:48.120 --> 00:10:53.221
especially people who have
visual impairments like low vision,

00:10:54.601 --> 00:10:57.990
hypermetropia, myopia,
people who need glasses

00:10:58.650 --> 00:11:03.654
to read things that are far away.
It can be very difficult for them as well.

00:11:03.655 --> 00:11:06.167
Now, how do we fix these issues?

00:11:07.951 --> 00:11:13.981
Using accessible fonts
that are 16 pixels and above for the body

00:11:14.071 --> 00:11:18.107
and making them scalable
will fix this typography issue.

00:11:19.274 --> 00:11:22.711
Fonts are overly stylized,
condensed, or compressed.

00:11:23.010 --> 00:11:27.301
When a wrong style of font
is used for a body

00:11:28.021 --> 00:11:32.759
in a way, and it is adjusted in a way,
either stretched or compressed in a way

00:11:32.760 --> 00:11:36.301
that fits a designer's aesthetic,
instead of making it usable,

00:11:36.931 --> 00:11:39.885
this can be an accessibility issue
in typography.

00:11:40.921 --> 00:11:42.270
How do we fix this issue?

00:11:42.630 --> 00:11:45.181
Avoid decorative fonts for the body.

00:11:45.541 --> 00:11:51.631
Instead, choose legible typefaces
with open letter forms.

00:11:53.491 --> 00:11:57.630
Another issue is low contrast
between text and background.

00:11:57.990 --> 00:12:04.111
Example, using light gray types
on a white background and vice versa.

00:12:05.220 --> 00:12:09.809
This can be a problem for users
who have visual impairments or users

00:12:09.810 --> 00:12:12.377
who are colorblind.

00:12:15.586 --> 00:12:20.280
To fix this issue, designers
must meet the WCA guideline

00:12:20.521 --> 00:12:22.711
for the contrast AA minimum,

00:12:22.951 --> 00:12:29.341
which states that text should be 4.5
is to 1 ratio for text,

00:12:29.730 --> 00:12:34.064
and 7.1 is to 1 ratio
for the bold text or headings.

00:12:35.595 --> 00:12:42.180
Finally, for typographical issues,
information shown only using color.

00:12:43.021 --> 00:12:46.217
When information or important emphases
are made using only color,

00:12:46.351 --> 00:12:51.587
for instance, links used
as blue without underlining,

00:12:52.081 --> 00:12:55.471
this can be confusing for users
who have learning disability

00:12:56.701 --> 00:12:58.050
or visual impairment.

00:12:58.441 --> 00:12:59.640
How do we fix this?

00:13:00.031 --> 00:13:01.665
Differentiate between links.

00:13:02.520 --> 00:13:05.967
Differentiate links with more than color.

00:13:05.968 --> 00:13:09.390
We can underline or use, or embolden them.

00:13:09.840 --> 00:13:11.971
Also, use headings,

00:13:12.211 --> 00:13:17.475
bullet points, and spacings
for easier scanning of text.

00:13:19.500 --> 00:13:25.169
This picture illustration on the screen
is a perfect example of a type

00:13:25.170 --> 00:13:32.911
of accessibility issue in typography,
like bad kerning or compressing of text,

00:13:33.421 --> 00:13:35.101
bad spacing of text.

00:13:36.450 --> 00:13:42.560
On the screen, the words furnace
and kernel are written down in Serif

00:13:42.561 --> 00:13:43.961
and Sans Serif forms.

00:13:44.760 --> 00:13:48.210
Because of the bad spacing
and compression,

00:13:48.511 --> 00:13:51.920
this word can be misread
as furmace and kermel,

00:13:51.921 --> 00:13:54.497
which can be an accessibility issue
in typography,

00:13:54.498 --> 00:13:58.759
which leads to wrong information
being communicated.

00:13:58.760 --> 00:14:04.111
This can also pose a problem for users
who either have learning disability

00:14:04.141 --> 00:14:06.337
or visual impairments.

00:14:08.407 --> 00:14:10.890
In iconography and imagery,

00:14:11.461 --> 00:14:14.640
when we talk about accessibility
in iconography and imagery,

00:14:14.880 --> 00:14:18.091
we're talking
about the familiarity of the icon sets,

00:14:18.390 --> 00:14:24.127
the illustrations to the users,
the ability to adapt

00:14:25.741 --> 00:14:27.241
these icon sets

00:14:27.810 --> 00:14:31.710
in physical forms
by adding texture, example,

00:14:31.890 --> 00:14:33.154
the traffic signpost,

00:14:33.540 --> 00:14:38.778
or the diversity and inclusion
that's implemented

00:14:38.779 --> 00:14:40.567
while creating this text.

00:14:42.104 --> 00:14:47.039
Considering people with disabilities,
foreigners who are new to your imagery

00:14:47.040 --> 00:14:52.507
or your icons, and next billion users
who are new to the internet in general.

00:14:54.342 --> 00:14:58.530
Now, let us talk about some of the issues
that can be seen in iconography

00:14:58.531 --> 00:14:59.531
and imagery.

00:15:00.030 --> 00:15:02.574
One of them is icons without labels

00:15:02.575 --> 00:15:05.611
that leave the interpretation up
to the user.

00:15:05.910 --> 00:15:10.290
Imagine a user who is new
to the internet, and he sees an icon

00:15:10.291 --> 00:15:14.090
that he has never seen before,
and that icon has no labels at all.

00:15:14.881 --> 00:15:17.828
Now, they are left to interpret
that icon on their own.

00:15:17.940 --> 00:15:20.587
Without having
any prior knowledge to this,

00:15:20.588 --> 00:15:24.030
it can be very difficult for them to get
whatever information you're trying

00:15:24.031 --> 00:15:25.921
to communicate with that icon.

00:15:26.160 --> 00:15:27.678
How do you fix these issues?

00:15:29.100 --> 00:15:35.541
Add labels or tooltips
to your icons for critical action.

00:15:37.191 --> 00:15:40.337
Overly abstract icons
not recognized globally.

00:15:41.538 --> 00:15:46.427
Some countries have icons
that are specifically for their region.

00:15:47.311 --> 00:15:54.458
Imagine using an icon or imagery
that is not recognizable

00:15:54.459 --> 00:15:58.861
to someone or a foreigner
who comes into a country

00:15:59.640 --> 00:16:01.165
and has not seen an icon before.

00:16:01.166 --> 00:16:03.870
This is going
to be very difficult for them

00:16:03.871 --> 00:16:06.720
to understand
whatever information you're trying

00:16:06.840 --> 00:16:09.810
to push, or whatever information
you're trying

00:16:09.822 --> 00:16:13.143
to communicate using your icon.

00:16:13.144 --> 00:16:14.551
How do you fix this?

00:16:15.210 --> 00:16:17.760
Use globally recognizable icons.

00:16:18.000 --> 00:16:22.789
For example, everybody knows
that magnifying glass means search.

00:16:25.890 --> 00:16:27.405
Another issue is low contrast

00:16:27.406 --> 00:16:30.385
or thin line icons that blur
when they're small.

00:16:32.456 --> 00:16:34.434
How do you fix this issue?

00:16:35.700 --> 00:16:39.031
Test your icons
as small sizes for clarity,

00:16:39.090 --> 00:16:40.705
and make sure they are scalable.

00:16:41.940 --> 00:16:45.896
Using pixel sizes from 16 to 24.

00:16:46.830 --> 00:16:51.713
Another issue, absence of
disability-inclusive and accessible icons,

00:16:52.021 --> 00:16:55.051
illustrations, and pictures
in visual displays.

00:16:55.920 --> 00:17:00.112
When you want to design
a poster for publicity,

00:17:00.690 --> 00:17:05.042
do you incorporate people
with disabilities in any imagery

00:17:05.043 --> 00:17:06.173
or pictures?

00:17:06.773 --> 00:17:10.492
Absence of these
is inaccessibility in imagery.

00:17:11.586 --> 00:17:12.840
How do you fix this?

00:17:13.740 --> 00:17:18.669
Add accessible icons, illustrations,
and disability-inclusive photos

00:17:18.670 --> 00:17:20.760
in your brand styles.

